column2: David Gandy Florida International University, Earth and Environment Department
column67: Western end of the C-113 canal and extending into the C-111 canal.  Large dense mats between S-176 and S-177 water control structures
column150: I did not take pictures of large clumps of hydrilla removed from lower unit of research vessel, however, samples were positively ID's as Hydrilla independently by myself and Lab manager of the Periphyton lab at FIU.  Mats were so dense in regions of the C-111 canal (including center of canal) that we had to remove large clumps from the lower unit of research vessel every couple 100 meters. Estimates of infested areas were made using measurements in Google Earth (canal w x length)- infestation appeared throughout entire canal between S-176 and S-177 water control structures.  Estimate does not include large dense mats infested in the western edge of C-113.

column2: Vital Signs Maine Gulf of Maine Research Institute Program
column150: Field Notes: LOCATION NOTE: In this case, the map marker is showing the waterbody that is infested, and NOT the exact point where the species was found.OBSERVATION DETAILS: Discovered by shorefront property owner. Hydrilla found throughout the lake, at least out to 6 feet deep. Herbicide treatments since 2003 have supressed hydrilla by 95 per cent each year. DEP biologists are determining whether tuber (seed) bank is being depleted sufficiently with continued treatments. 2010 dive survey found no hydrilla.. Sampling Method: Just looking around

column2: Vital Signs Maine Gulf of Maine Research Institute Program
column150: Field Notes: LOCATION NOTE: In this case, the map marker is showing the waterbody that is infested, and NOT the exact point where the species was found. OBSERVATION DETAILS: Discovered by Invasive Plant Patroller early September 2009 and confirmed by VLMP and DEP next day. Infestation limited to 0.3-acre lagoon and several plants just outside lagoon on west side of Lake, just north of narrows. DEP fenced off two outlets connected to Lake in September and conducted two days of manual (hand) removal within lagoon and deployed benthic barriers on plants just outside lagoon in October. DEP permanently closed off one of the two outlets with rip-rap stone. Damaricotta Lake Watershed Association has mobilized volunteers for Lake survey in 2010. No hydrilla found elsewhere. Also in 2010, DEP controlled infestation with herbicide treatment within the .3-acre lagoon, surveillance and manual (hand) removal of plants from nearby cove and deployment of benthic barriers in lagoon for long-term hydrilla suppression.. Sampling Method: Just looking around

column2: Vital Signs Maine Gulf of Maine Research Institute Program
column67: Watershed: Other, Water Temperature: 16.1, pH: 9, Dissolved oxygen: 6
column150: Field Notes: For years we've been on the lookout for Maine's 10 most unwanted aquatic nuisance species, and alas, it appears we have a sighting of the most aggressive of them all - hydrilla.   Thanks to the efforts of volunteer lake monitors, this particular area of infestation was detected early, and is believed to be contained within a small lagoon area.  This area has been cordoned off by DEP personnel to prevent spread, while a decision is being made on a longer term course of action.  Sampling of a nearby similar lagoon provides initial confirmation that this sighting may be the only area of infestation, but more sampling of the entire lake will be needed, now and again in the next year(s).  See second observation for comparison habitat characteristics and photos for the lagoon that appears hydrilla-free, located less than 300 yards away from this site.. Sampling Method: Just looking around.  Size: Greater than 10 cm

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: nice ramp w/dock, clear visability, 2 unidentified plants, dominated by 3 spp. milfoil, chara and unidentified. Looks like lake was sprayed, lots of dead chara and milfoil.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: Launch within wildlife refuge. Abundant filamentous algae.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: Abundant plant life in and around the boat launch. Plant life lessons as water gets deeper, abundant filamentous algea. Large well-kept parking lot and boat ramp. Curly leaf growing in one patch next to boat ramp in very shallow water.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: Unidentified plant present, launch is dried up and lily choked about 1/4 mile.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: Low visibility. Mainly residential shoreline. Delapidated dock. Abundant filamentous algae.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: potomogeton/nuphar spp. observed visually by RTUS, gravel ramp, high turbidity/no diving.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: Low visibility. Abundant Filamentous Algae

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: no submerged vegetation observed, high TSS, small cement ramp

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: Shoreline restoration project in progress.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: large ramp w/ adjoining marina, heavy recreation, swam around marina, holds 200 boats, 2 (100ft) break waters, 2nd rake toss 1,2,3, off dock b/c no left access to ramp.  Turf surrounds majority of parking lot.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: High TSS at launch, majority of basin survey 1 meter depth, no plants.  Rake toss protocol failed to gather M. Spicatum. Launch surrounded by public park.  Launch located in creek attached to resevoir (not like in map) no flow observed.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
column150: Water determined low visibility, high TSS preformed IL protocol.  M. spicatum and C. diversum visually abundant.  All plants covered with a muddy algal substance, boat launch shallow basin heading to lake, car bridge.

column2: Central Hardwoods Invasive Plant Network CHIP-N Joint Aquatic Invasive Species Survey
